Hands-on experience beneficial in job search

There’s an old saying that tells us “experi—
ence is the best teacher.” In today’s compet-
itive job market, it can also be said that
experience is the best employment refer-
ence. Increasingly, recruiters are selecting
graduating students who have combined
academics with practical, hands-on experi-
ence.

- Graduates with a work history have sev-
eral key advantages. Past or current

employment demonstrates a willingness to

put in the time and energy needed to be a
successful employee and provides a source
of references from former supervisors who
can attest to the candidate’s skills and abili-

_ ties. And if summer or part-time work

helped to pay the bills through college, it
gives potential employers an insight to your
character. C

Probably the best type of work experi-

ence is an internship or co-op assignment,
where you can work in a field or industry
that interests you. These types of jobs may
lead‘ to offers of permanent employment
after graduation. At the very least, they
allow you to develop skills that are valued
by many companies — writing, project
team experience or programming skills, just

to name a few. In many cases, you can even '

earn academic credits for successful corn-
pletion of the job. The School of

~ Engineering has its own co-op program —

information about opportunities and eligi-

bility can be obtained in room 749
Benedum Hall. Other students should stop
by the Internship Office in room 1-40
Thackeray Hall.

Some of the most valuable work experi-
ences can be found through volunteering. If
you can afford the time and don't need the
cash, you can often find an unpaid position
that gives you a lot of management respon-
sibility and administrative discretion. The
fact that it’s a volunteer experience won’t

The
Placement
Center

matter to recruiters — they’ll focus on what
you did, not how much you made. Best of
all, you’ll have a chance to perform some
worthwhile community service while you’re
building your resume. Contact some local

nonprofit organizations and find out what S

opportunities are available. An excellent
source for accessing these organizations is a
publication called Where To Turn, pub-
lished by the United Way. It’s available at
the reference desk in Hillman Library. And
don’t overlook the Pitt campus —— leader-
ship positions in activities are prime exam-
ples of unpaid experiences that can pay off

handsomely at graduation.

If your work experiences through college
will probably be limited to fast-food restau-
rants and landscaping crews, take heart.
Many of the corporate recruiters that you’ll
interview with probably did similar work
while they were in school. And you can still
get a lot of mileage out of “nonrelevant”
types of jobs. The trick is in how you pre-
sent your experiences to potential employ-
ers. _

For example, waitressing at a restaurant

can either be described to an interviewer as

“waiting on tables,” or as a position requir-
ing strong customer service, versatility, an
ability to work under pressure and the skills
to resolve problems quickly and profession-
ally. For an extensive listing of part-tiine
employment opportunities, visit the Student
Employment Office at room 200 in the
William Pitt Union.

One last tip. While you’re working a suin-
mer or part-time job, always keep your eyes
open for opportunities to expand your
knowledge. Take the time to find out what
other people in the organization do and
learn all that you can. 0

Discovering the basics of writing grant
proposals or using a computer software
package may .not increase your hourly
wage, but it can help turn that mundane job
into something special when you’re inter-
viewing during your senior year.

 

