H isiory repeated

Although our generation stresses “education, it seems
we don’t want to learn from our mistakes. History is the
best teacher around, and it seems we’ve been sleeping
through class. 

Not even 50 years ago, atrocities like the ones now
happening in the former Yugoslavia were being com-
mitted in the same part of the world. And once again,
by and large, the international community is doing the
same thing. Nothing. 1

The U.S. Holocaust Museum opened this year in
Washington, D.C., to eternalize the memory of the mil-
lions of Jews, Poles, homosexuals, Gypsies and others
who were slaughtered during the wake of the Nazi
machine. ;

Yet, we want to turn the other cheek on the Bosnian-

Muslims who are meeting the same fate today.

We have a stake in the fate of these people. They are
a part of the human family. And if we don’t do some-
thing, who knows when it will end?

By this time, one would think that the human race
would be mature enough to realize this behavior cannot
go on. According to relief experts, there will be tens of
thousands of additional deaths on top of the tens of
thousands who are already dead.’

If there is no action taken, our generation will be full

of nothing but cowards with no sense of morality and .

compassion. -

Hopes were rekindled a few weeks ago with the for-
mulation of a partition plan in Geneva, Switzerland to
end the fighting between the Serbs, Croats and Muslims.
But recent developments show the Bosnian govern-
ment forces battling on.

According to the Sept. 13 issue of the US. News and
World Report, support is growing in Washington to lift
the arms embargo and formulate international policy to
defend the victims. _

No one wants to see any deployment of American
troops to the region for fear that American. lives might
be lost. But at certain times in history the moment will
arise when sacriﬁces must be made in order to have a
brighter future.

By no means should America carry the load itself.

However, the international community looks to the
United States for leadership. President Clinton, whether
he likes it or not,‘ has to be the man to provide the
impetus for an international effort to help bring about a
solution. , ’

We have many things on our minds today, and the
tendency to forget what is going on around us is
extremely common. I
‘ But the human race is in jeopardy.

Stand up for what is right and just. Let your voice be
heard by the decision makers in this country. Let’s make
it so colleges and universities set the tone for social con-
sciousness in America once again.

