Wielding catgut-strung rack- .

ets, the Pitt men’s tennis team
enters the new season intent
on clawing and scratching its

, way out of the conference dog-

house.

Entering the -season without
three of last year’s top six play-
ers, the Panthers will be relying
heavily on a touted cast of first—
year players to improve on last
season’s last place finish at the
Big East Conference
Championships. '

"We want to get out of last
place,” said head coach George
Dieffenbach. “That’s why we
recruited the players we did,
and why we’ll work real hard
this year.”

First-year recruits Braden
Doherty, Brad Wade and Matt
Mills all come into the season
with legitimate shots of break-
ing into the starting six before
the first match Thursday at St.

 

Francis. _

Doherty comes to Pitt as the
eighth-ranked junior player in
Ontario, Canada, while Wade is
a former WPIAL champion.

“I just want a stable place in
the starting lineup, so I can
contribute to a winning sea-
son,” Doherty said.

In addition to the recruits,
Pitt is returning Jeff Campbell,
James Chronister, David
Dumpel and Chris McShane
from last season's team, which,
despite the last-place Big East
finish, was 10-4 in head-to-
head matches.

Campbell, a senior, is the top
veteran after playing No. 4 last
season.

“We have a more cohesive
team this year,” said Campbell.
“Every person is equal on this

, team.”

With the potential of having
three first—year players in the
starting six, there is the ques-
tion of having an inexperi-
enced team. But Dieffenbach
dispels this notion.

“We have a nice combination
of experience and youth,” he
said. “Besides, the freshmen are
tough tournament competitors.
They have enough experience
to step in and play well.”

Doherty seems to believe his
coach. -
“We’re all really into it,” he
said. “It’s the first year of a new

cycle, and we’re going to work
hard at winning.”

Unlike Pitt’s revenue sports,
the tennis team doesn’t get to
play a regular season Big East
schedule. Pitt will face
Georgetown at the Pitt
Invitational in February and

. Rutgers in April, but won’t face

the other Big East teams until
the conference championships
at the end of April.

“We can’t afford to travel,”
said Campbell. “But we have a
competitive schedule outside
the conference. We’ll be
ready.”

Ready to fight its way out of
the Big East cellar? It’s going to
be a gut—check» year for the
Panther tennis program.

